## Distribution of lymph node metastasis and oncological outcomes of mid- transverse colon cancer: extended versus transverse colectomy

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## Abstract

Aim: The optimal surgical method for cancer of the mid- transverse colon has not been well established. The present study aimed to explore the distribution of lymph node metastasis and compare the outcomes of extended and transverse colectomies for cancer of the mid- transverse colon.

Methods: We  retrospectively  analysed  the  data  of  patients  with  cancer  of  the  midtransverse  colon  treated  with  either  an  extended  hemicolectomy  (right  or  left)  or  a transverse colectomy. A propensity score matching analysis was performed to rule out selection bias, and short- term and survival outcomes were compared. The distribution of lymph node metastasis was also investigated.

Results: A  total  of  107  patients  were  included,  70  of  whom  underwent  an  extended colectomy while 37 underwent a transverse colectomy. There were no significant differences in the operation time, postoperative complications, hospital stay, 3- year diseasefree survival (86.5% vs. 90.9%, P = 0.675) and 5- year overall survival (87.4% vs. 93.0%, P = 0.349) between the two groups after propensity score matching. However, metastases were observed in the lymph nodes along the right colic artery (pericolic [#211], 14.0%; intermediate [#212], 8.2%; apical [#213], 9.8%) in the extended colectomy group.

Conclusion: Extended and transverse colectomies showed similar short- term and longterm outcomes for mid- transverse colon cancer. However, care should be taken to determine the extent of resection considering the possibility of metastatic lymph nodes along the right colic artery.

## What does this paper add to the literature?

This paper analysed the distribution of lymph node metastases and the outcomes of extended and transverse colectomies in mid- transverse colon cancer. We found that there was no significant difference in postoperative complications and the survival outcomes between the two groups, and there were significant lymph node metastases along the right colic artery in mid- transverse colon cancer.

## INTRODUCTION

Radical surgery is the treatment of choice for resectable colorectal cancer. The surgical approach for transverse colon cancer involves technical difficulties and a high risk of complication because the area is sensitive to ischaemia and is closely attached to the surrounding organs  [1,2].  Consequently,  there  are  few  studies  on  transverse colon cancer, and it has been excluded from large prospective trials compared to other colorectal cancers [3- 7], although transverse colon cancer accounts for 10% of all colorectal cancers [8,9].

Several  previous  studies  have  attempted  to  determine  the most desirable surgical treatment for mid- transverse colon cancer [2,10,11];  however,  the  optimal  surgical  method  is  not  yet  established.  Some  studies  have  shown  that  transverse  colectomy  is  as safe and feasible as an extended colectomy [2,12,13]; nevertheless, others  explained  that  there  was  a  significant  difference  between the two surgical methods in terms of postoperative morbidity and oncological outcomes [10,11]. Hence, the surgical method adopted largely depends on the surgeon's preference and experience.

The aim of this retrospective study was to explore the distribution of lymph node (LN) metastases and evaluate the short- term and long- term  outcomes  of  extended  and  transverse  colectomies  for cancer of the mid- transverse colon to determine the optimal surgical approach.

## METHODS

This study was approved by the Institutional Review Board of our institution. We retrospectively reviewed the data of patients who underwent  either  an  extended  hemicolectomy  (right  or  left)  or  a transverse colectomy for mid- transverse colon cancer in our institution between May 2005 and December 2015. Patients with familial adenomatous polyposis, hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer, metachronous  cancer  and  histological  type  other  than  adenocarcinoma,  and  those  who  underwent  emergency  surgery,  were  excluded. Mid- transverse colon cancer is defined as a tumour located in the middle one- third of the transverse colon. Tumours located at either flexure were excluded. The mid- transverse location was determined by both preoperative imaging and surgical exploration.

Transverse  colectomy  was  defined  as  resecting  a  part  of  the colon between the hepatic flexure and splenic flexure while ligating the origin of the middle colic pedicle, which provides vascular supply to  the  intestine.  Both  flexures  were  mobilized  in  most  cases,  and end- to- side anastomosis was made using a circular and a linear stapler. Extended colectomies included both extended right hemicolectomy and extended left hemicolectomy. The ileocolic pedicle and the middle colic vessels were ligated at their origin with dissection of LNs along the superior mesenteric vein to perform the extended right hemicolectomy. If the ileocolic artery ran behind the superior mesenteric vein, the ileocolic artery was ligated at the level of the right border of the superior mesenteric vein, according to previous literature  [14].  In  most  cases  of  extended  left  hemicolectomy,  the

left colic pedicles and the root of the middle colic vessels were ligated.  As  specified  in  the  American  Joint  Committee  on  Cancer (AJCC) Cancer Staging Manual (8th edition), the regional LNs of the mid- transverse colon were distributed along the middle colic artery [15]. Thus, under the principle of sufficient dissection of mid colic LNs, the surgical method was determined at the surgeon's discretion, considering the length of the transverse colon and its relationship to the surrounding organs. Even if LN metastasis was suspected along the middle colic artery, transverse colectomy was allowed if radical resection was possible. Based on the desirable principle of colon cancer surgery, complete mesocolic excision [16] and D3 LN dissection [17] were routinely performed.

Histopathological examination was performed by an experienced pathologist according to the standard procedures. The pathological staging was determined using the classification system of the AJCC 7th edition. Based on the Japanese classification of colorectal carcinoma, LNs were categorized and indicated by number according to each location. The position of mesocolic LNs was represented by a three- digit number in the 200s. The units digit indicated the group, with pericolic LNs indicated by 1, intermediate LNs by 2 and apical LNs at the origin by 3. The tens digit represented the associated artery, with the ileocolic artery classified as 0, right colic artery as 1, middle colic artery as 2 and left colic artery as 3 [18]. The ileocolic artery was defined as the terminal branch of the superior mesenteric artery, and the right colic artery was defined as the artery that sup plies blood to the right colon, which was located between the middle colic and ileocolic arteries. The right colic artery included the branch from the ileocolic or middle colic artery as well as the branch from the superior mesenteric artery. The middle colic artery was defined as the first large right branch of the superior mesenteric artery, and the accessory middle colic artery was also included if it existed [19].

For  advanced  colon  cancer,  adjuvant  chemotherapy  was  recommended  after  considering  the  patient's  systemic  condition. Follow- up examinations, including laboratory test for serum carcinoembryonic antigen, chest CT and abdominopelvic CT, were conducted every 6 months. Surveillance colonoscopy was performed in the first, third and fifth years after surgery. Recurrence was defined as the reappearance of the disease identified on clinical, radiological or pathological examination. Disease- free survival (DFS) was calculated as the time from surgery to the date of recurrence or death. Overall survival (OS) was measured as the period from surgery to death from any cause.

A propensity score matching analysis was performed to rule out selection bias. Propensity scores were calculated based on a logistic regression model, including age, sex, body mass index, surgical approach, tumour size and pathological T and N stages. Subsequently, patients who underwent transverse colectomy were matched with patients  who  underwent  extended  colectomy  according  to  propensity  scores.  Clinical  data,  including  clinicopathological  characteristics, surgical outcomes and postoperative complications, were analysed to compare the short- term outcomes. Based on the distribution of data, comparisons of continuous variables were performed by Student's t test  or  the  Mann- Whitney U test.  The /uni03C7 2 test  and

Fisher's exact test were used to analyse the categorical variables. The Kaplan- Meier method was used to estimate survival outcomes. All results were considered clinically significant at values of P <0.05. Statistical  analyses  were  performed  using  SPSS  software  version 25.0 (IBM Inc., Armonk, New York, USA).

## RESULTS

Baseline characteristics of the patients are presented in Table 1. Of the  107  patients,  70  (65.4%)  patients  underwent  extended  colectomy, while 37 (34.6%) patients underwent transverse colectomy. In the extended colectomy group, 65 patients underwent extended right  hemicolectomy  and  five  patients  underwent  extended  left hemicolectomy. Baseline characteristics showed no difference between the two groups, except in the surgical approach (open surgery,

20.0% vs. 43.2%, P = 0.011). Clinical N stage also showed no difference between the two groups ( P = 0.772), and there was no patient with suspicious metastatic LNs along the ileocolic or left colic artery. After propensity score matching, there was no difference between the groups in any of the variables.

The short- term  outcomes  after  propensity  score  matching  are shown in Table 2. There were no differences in the operation time (141.4  43.1 vs. 141.4  41.5 min; P = 0.997), postoperative com plications (43.2% vs. 32.4%; P = 0.338) and length of stay (9.4  5.2 vs. 9.5  5.2 days; P =  0.965) between the two groups. The mean number of LNs harvested was significantly higher in the extended colectomy group (44.0  23.6 vs. 21.4  16.9; P <  0.001), and the proportion of patients with <12 harvested LNs was significantly different between the two groups (2.7% vs. 32.4%; P = 0.001). The longitudinal resection margin in the extended colectomy group was also significantly longer (7.8  5.1 vs. 4.9  2.3 cm; P = 0.003).

## DISCUSSION

We analysed the distribution of LN metastases and the outcomes of extended and transverse colectomies in mid- transverse colon cancer. The results showed that there was no significant difference in postoperative complications and the survival outcomes between the two groups, except in the proportion of patients with <12 harvested LNs,  which  was  significantly  higher  in  the  transverse  colectomy group. In addition, there was considerable LN metastasis (14.0% in #211, 8.2% in #212 and 9.8% in #213) along the right colic artery.

Although previous studies reported that the 5- year OS ranged from 50% to 61% in transverse colon cancer [6,20], recent studies showed improved survival outcomes in mid- transverse colon cancer. Some studies revealed that the 5- year DFS was comparable between extended and transverse colectomies (90.1% vs. 87.0%, P = 0.924; 92.4% vs. 95.7%, P = 0.593) [2,10], while others showed a signifi -cant difference in 3- year DFS, with 78.1% for transverse colectomy and 86.1% for right extended hemicolectomy ( P < 0.001) [11]. In our study,  long- term  oncological  outcomes  were  similar  between  the

two groups after propensity score matching. The difference in these results might be due to the different designs of each study, and fur ther large- scale prospective studies are required to draw concrete conclusions.

There  are  inadequate  data  to  compare  the  rate  of  recurrence of mid- transverse colon cancer following extended and transverse colectomies.  Matsuda  et  al.  [10]  reported  that  the  LN  recurrence was so insignificant that a statistical comparison was difficult. Some other  studies  revealed  a  significantly  higher  rate  of  recurrence  in the  transverse  colectomy  group  after  propensity  score  matching (0% vs. 12.5%, P =  0.039) [2]. However, that study was limited by small  sample  size,  a  significantly  higher  number  of  patients  with poor tumour grade in the transverse colectomy group (0% vs. 15.6%, P = 0.021) and a higher proportion of patients who received adjuvant chemotherapy in the extended colectomy group (28.1% vs. 12.5%, P = 0.120). Hence, it is difficult to conclude the impact of the surgical method on recurrence.

Surgery for  curative  treatment  of  colorectal  cancer  should  include an adequate extent of lymphadenectomy. LN metastasis along the right  colic  artery  in  mid- transverse  colon  cancer  has  been  reported in previous studies. Park et al. [21] reported that 11.4% of patients with transverse colon cancer had LN metastases in #211, 7.7% in # 212 and 7.6% in #213, while there was no metastasis to LNs along the ileocolic artery. Yada et al. [22] reported that LN metastasis was limited to the middle colic artery if the transverse colon cancer was located on the left side of that artery; however, metastases were observed along the right colic artery in 16.7% of patients with a tumour on the right side of the artery. Our study also confirmed

LN metastasis along the right colic artery in mid- transverse colon cancer, while there was no LN metastasis along the ileocolic artery and left colic artery. These results indicate that lymphadenectomy was necessary along the right colic artery in mid- transverse colon cancer, and transverse colectomy might be inadequate as a definitive treatment method.

Harvesting of at least 12 LNs has been suggested by guidelines for colon cancer surgery, to prevent underestimation of LN involvement  [23].  Regarding  mid- transverse  colon  cancer,  some  authors showed no significant difference with a minimal harvest of 12 LNs [2],  while  others  suggested  that  the  number  of  patients  with  <12 harvested  LNs  was  expected  to  account  for  a  significantly  larger number in the transverse colectomy group [10]. The present study showed  that  the  proportion  of  patients  with  <12  harvested  LNs was significantly higher in the transverse colectomy group (2.7% vs. 32.4%, P = 0.001), which might affect not only the pathological stage and the administration of adjuvant therapy but also the oncological outcomes.

Previous studies on mid- transverse colon cancer reported different rates of postoperative complications in extended and transverse colectomies. Leijssen et al. [2] reported that patients in the extended colectomy group had a higher rate of complications, although the difference was statistically insignificant (49.1% vs. 39.5%, P = 0.337). They explained that this observation might be due to a higher rate of postoperative ileus and a higher need for blood transfusion after extended  colectomy.  However,  Matsuda  et  al.  [10]  reported  that there was a significantly higher rate of postoperative complications after laparoscopic transverse colectomy than after laparoscopic extended right hemicolectomy (10.5% vs. 29.4%, P = 0.014). In addi tion, Milone et al. [11] also showed a higher rate of complications in the transverse colectomy group (23.6% vs. 30.1%, P =  0.01). They suggested  that  these  might  be  due  to  the  technical  difficulty  for adequate lymphadenectomy during transverse colectomy and the mobilization of both splenic flexure and hepatic flexure. Our study showed no significant difference in postoperative complications between the two groups after propensity score matching (43.2% vs. 32.4%, P = 0.338). It is possible that the difference in the sample size of each study and the difference in the distribution of the type of laparoscopic surgery led to different results.

The present study had several limitations. First, the definition of the right colic artery may be ambiguous due to anatomical variations. However, we used the same definition of the right colic artery as previous studies [19]. In addition, the proportion of the existence of the right colic artery (77%, 50/65) was similar compared with previous  studies  (60%- 80%)  [19],  which  means  that  the  definition  of the right colic artery was appropriately used. Second, the number of patients included was small because this study focused on midtransverse colon cancer, excluding cancer of the hepatic flexure and splenic flexure. Third, our study was a retrospective study, and selection bias cannot be ruled out. However, we conducted a propensity score matching analysis to overcome these concerns. In addition, our study reported the possibility of metastasis to the right colic LNs based on the distribution of LN metastasis of mid- transverse colon

cancer and suggested relevant oncological outcomes. A multicentre study involving a large number of patients is necessary to suggest an optimal surgical method due to the low incidence of mid- transverse colon cancer.

In  conclusion,  extended  and  transverse  colectomies  showed similar short- term outcomes and survival results for mid- transverse colon cancer. However, care should be taken to determine the extent of resection, considering possible metastasis to the right colic LNs.
